{
  "query": "How does the evidence for using acoustically reflective materials on fishing gear compare to attaching acoustically reflective objects for reducing marine mammal entanglement?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence, using acoustically reflective materials in fishing gear (action 2807) shows more promising results for reducing marine mammal entanglements compared to attaching acoustically reflective objects to fishing gear (action 2806). \n\nFor acoustically reflective materials: Five studies evaluated this approach. Two controlled studies in Canadian waters found mixed behavioral responses - harbour porpoises used fewer echolocation clicks at barium sulfate nets but approached both types of nets similarly, and echolocation activity was similar at both net types. More importantly for entanglement reduction, two of three controlled studies found nets made from acoustically reflective materials (iron-oxide or barium sulfate) had fewer entanglements of harbour porpoises than conventional nets, though one study found no reduction in dolphin entanglements with barium sulfate nets.\n\nFor attached acoustic reflectors: Only two studies were available. One controlled study in Australian waters found that attaching metallic bead chains to fishing nets did not reduce dolphin entanglements, while another study in the Gulf of Alaska found that attaching acrylic beads next to fishing hooks did not reduce sperm whale predation on fish catches.\n\nThe evidence base is larger for integrated acoustically reflective materials (5 studies) compared to attached objects (2 studies), with the material approach showing some successful entanglement reductions in certain contexts, while the attached objects approach showed no effectiveness in the limited studies conducted.",
